We hope you all have a wonderful Father’s Day. Tune in for a thoughtful conversation about Father’s Day with my friend and podcast co-host, Scott Schimmel. We talk on the importance of dads, how to honor them, and how to become a better one. To all the great dads out there, we’re cheering you on. If this day is hard for you, we are with you.
 
For more videos of hope, join us for Bob Weekly: bobgoff.com/weekly

node.text:
I want to personally thank everyone who made this ambitious project we started in Afghanistan in these past years work. It’s been so fun doing this for the kids together.
Repost from @lovedoes 🎈

Due to conflict in Afghanistan, many families had to flee their homes, halting kids education in the process. This country has faced some difficulties, but we see tremendous hope on the faces of these students.

Thanks to your love and generosity, this year we finished the construction of our brand new school building! The students and staff love their bright new space, and it has been a wonderful encouragement to them all throughout the pandemic.

This school will make an incredible impact on this community for generations to come, and you make it possible!

Video by @halleproject.

Thank you @lauren_daigle for making our newest @lovedoes school possible in the Congo! We've been working hard building the school with our friends and partners at @Justice_Rising. Lauren's foundation The Price Fund has generously made this a reality and we are so thankful!

node.text:
Today on the Dream Big Podcast I am joined by Father Richard Rohr who is a Franciscan Friar, multiple New York Time’s best-selling author and founder of the Center for Action and Contemplation (CAC) in Albuquerque, New Mexico. 

For over fifty years, Father Richard’s personal experience of God’s infinite and transforming love has inspired his lifelong work of helping to remove the barriers that keep people from knowing God’s love for themselves. 

Come listen to our conversation wherever you get your podcasts.

node.text: We are continuing to lift up our students, teachers, staff and those courageous men and women in uniform who doing the immensely difficult and life threatening work of protecting them. There are many things happening each day to get people to safety and we will be able to fill you in later on these efforts. We are so grateful for how you have loved the @lovedoes kids and your neighbors both near and far.

node.text:
In the wise words of my pal, Taylor Hughes, "Your life is not a puzzle to be solved, it is a mystery to enjoy!" Sometimes we need to be redirected to be able to see the wonder happening all around us. 

Taylor Hughes fell in love with the art of illusion when his parents bought him a magic kit for his 7th birthday. More than 30 years and 3,000 shows later, Taylor has become known for his signature style of Magic Storytelling. He is a favorite at Hollywood’s famed Magic Castle, a highly sought after Keynote Presenter and has a special on Amazon Prime called '“Chasing Wonder”.

Listen in to our conversation on the Dream Big Podcast and pre-order Taylor’s new book, The Road to Wonder: Finding the Extra in Your Ordinary.

node.text:
Although we can't predict or control what happens to us, we can certainly choose how we'll respond. Nobody more beautifully demonstrates that then my dear friend, Katherine Wolf, who joins me on the Dream Big Podcast today.

Katherine is a communicator and advocate. She married her husband Jay in 2004 and moved to Los Angeles to pursue a career in the entertainment industry. Their son, James was born in 2007, and six months later Katherine's life nearly ended with a catastrophic stroke. Miraculously, she survived and continues her recovery to this day, including having a miracle baby, John in 2015. Katherine and Jay have shared their journey of steadfast hope through their books, Hope Heals and Suffer Strong, and at speaking events both live and online before millions. Together, they founded Hope Heals camp, a community for families with disabilities like them. To connect, visit @hopeheals or hopeheals.com. 

Listen in where you stream podcasts.

We are lifting up our dear friends in Afghanistan and the children in our school there today. You have probably heard that the Taliban have taken over many cities this week, including one in which we have been working for a number of years.
I have turned off the comments section below, but we know that you are with our courageous Afghan friends, the children, the teachers and the families affected.
We’re sad, but filled with resolve knowing that the children remain the bright hope for this country.
